(t
 "**Clarifying legal terminology**\n\nI'm exploring the term \"roe,\" which refers to fish eggs and deer. In legal contexts, it's often paired with \"doe,\" suggesting a connection to hunted game. The name \"John Doe\" dates back to around the 16th century, first appearing in 1520. It originates from fictitious names used in English common-law actions for ejectment, where John Doe and Richard Roe represented the parties involved. Jane Doe emerged as a female counterpart in the 20th century, chosen for its arbitrariness and traditional use."
 "“John Doe” (and its companion name “Richard Roe”) comes from **English common-law procedure**, especially the old **action of ejectment** (used to recover possession of land) from roughly the **16th–19th centuries**.\n\n### Origin in ejectment lawsuits\nTo get around rigid medieval pleading rules, lawyers turned land disputes into a kind of legal fiction:\n\n- The real owner (A) would claim he had **leased** the land to a fictitious tenant, **John Doe**.\n- A second fictitious character, **Richard Roe**, would be alleged to have **ejected** (thrown out) John Doe.\n- John Doe would then sue Richard Roe.  \nThis let the court decide who really had the right to the land, while using simplified forms.\n\nBecause these names were used constantly as **placeholders**, “John Doe” gradually became a general label for:\n- an **unknown person**,\n- an **unidentified defendant**,\n- an **unidentified body** (in modern police/medical usage).\n\n### Where “Jane Doe” comes from\n“Jane Doe” is essentially a **later, female counterpart** adopted when courts, police, and media wanted an equivalent placeholder for an unknown woman. It’s much more modern in common usage than “John Doe,” but it’s built directly on the established “Doe” convention.\n\n### Why “Doe”?\nThere isn’t a single provable “because X” reason, but the best-supported explanation is:\n\n- **“Doe” and “Roe” were a matched pair** of short, generic, unmistakably fictitious names used by lawyers.\n- They’re also **common nouns** (a *doe* is a female deer; a *roe* is a kind of deer), which likely made them feel “non-real” and memorable as stock legal characters.\n\nSo “Doe” stuck not because it has a deep meaning in law, but because it became **traditional** through repeated use in those standard legal fictions.")
